SIMPLE: purge
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Purge
<hw>Purge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Purged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Purging</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>purger</ets>, L. <ets>purgare</ets>; <ets>purus</ets> pure +
<ets>agere</ets> to make, to do. See <er>Pure</er>, and
<er>Agent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cleanse, clear, or purify by
separating and carrying off whatever is impure, heterogeneous, foreign,
or superfluous.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Till fire <xex>purge</xex> all things
new.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To operate on as, or by means of,
a cathartic medicine, or in a similar manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To clarify; to defecate, as liquors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To clear of sediment, as a boiler, or of air, as a
steam pipe, by driving off or permitting escape.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To clear from guilt, or from moral or ceremonial
defilement; <as>as, to <ex>purge</ex> one of guilt or
crime</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When that he hath <qex>purged</qex> you from sin.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Purge</qex> me with hyssop, and I shall be clean.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. li. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To clear from accusation, or the
charge of a crime or misdemeanor, as by oath or in ordeal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To remove in cleansing; to deterge; to wash away; --
often followed by <xex>away</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Purge</qex> away our sins, for thy name's sake.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. lxxix. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We 'll join our cares to <qex>purge</qex> away⟦br⟧
Our country's crimes.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Purge
<hw>Purge</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become pure, as by
clarification.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To have or produce frequent evacuations from the
intestines, as by means of a cathartic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Purge
<hw>Purge</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>purge</ets>. See
<er>Purge</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
purging.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The preparative for the <qex>purge</qex> of paganism of the
kingdom of Northumberland.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which purges; especially, a medicine that
evacuates the intestines; a cathartic.</def>
<rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purger</ent>⟦br⟧
